The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet message about a possible buyout.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The value of the stock of $420 was supposedly set "due to the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the commission's co-director of security, Stephen Peikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the allegations of fraud unfounded, and added that he is very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
"Honesty is the most important value of my life, and the facts will prove that I have not violated this in any way," the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
