On September 30, 1928, exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of an era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the release of penicillin from mold fungi was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, while having a cold, he had sown mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (this is the kind of glass cap in which bacteria are experimented with) and a few days later discovered that the bacteria that were there had been destroyed.
Almost by chance he was found and penicillin.
Fleming's name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
