Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
Konstantin Kosachev, head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs, considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly a success for Russia and does not rule out that it can become a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric, which we have almost become accustomed to in recent years with regard to Russia, has now been much more muted," the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in previous years Russia was sometimes "designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least, in the presentation of the group of Western countries, which on this matter was quite unanimous."
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent."
"If we carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the German Foreign Minister, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was not exactly accurate," - the politician noted, noting that Russia "was no longer some wall about which the tennis ball is trained."
The head of the Profile Committee of the Council does not rule out that this indicates a trend, which, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session of the UN General Assembly, although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, in two, three".
"I do not rule out that this session in some sense can be a turning point," Kosachev admitted, explaining that "there are too many examples of Russia's involvement moving forward in international affairs."
He cited the situation in Syria, Iran and North Korea as an example.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," the MP added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an "adequate, sound perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of our time."
"I don't want to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that we are somewhere passing the point behind which the movement will no longer be a movement to reverse, it will be a movement forward," he added.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context Kosachev called "the request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop."
"I attended a lot of meetings of the head of the Russian delegation (at the session of the General Assembly) of Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different," - said the chairman of the committee of the Council of Ministers.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve the world's problems because of the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problem of nuclear non-proliferation, the problem of migration."
"And here the request for the Russian vision becomes more and more obvious," Kosachev expressed confidence, stressing that in this sense "the current session is successful for the work of the Russian delegation, which is good for Russia."
