Macedonian opposition leader refuses to vote in referendum
A referendum on an intergovernmental agreement with Greece on the renaming of the Republic of Macedonia is taking place in Macedonia on Sunday, September 30.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting an agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Greek Republic?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party, the Inner Macedonian Revolutionary Organization , the Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity (VMRO-DPMNE) Christian Mitskoski, stated that he would not vote in the referendum.
As explained by the party's spokesman Naum Stoilkowski, Mitskoski decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "pernicious".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum decides on the renaming of the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gheorghe Ivanov refused to take part in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in the referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created," Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of Northern Macedonia - was signed by the foreign ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shores of Lake Prespa, which runs the border between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, TASS reminds.
